9-26}}</ref>\n|gpu =\n|modem = [[Dual SIM]] with [[eSIM]]<br /> Gigabit-Class LTE Cat.19 with 4x4 MIMO, up to 30 [[LTE frequency bands|LTE bands]]\n|memory = 4 GB LPDDR4X RAM<ref name=\"MacRumors\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2019/09/17/iphone-11-pro-max-battery-mah-4gb-ram-tenaa/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Models Have Up to 25% Larger Batteries and 4GB of RAM Per Reliable TENAA Filings|access-date=2019-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918002119/https://www.macrumors.com/2019/09/17/iphone-11-pro-max-battery-mah-4gb-ram-tenaa/|archive-date=2019-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|storage = 64, 256 or 512 [[Gigabytes|GB]]\n|memory_card = None\n|battery = '''11 Pro''': 3.83 V 11.67 Wh (3046 mAh) [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion]]<ref name=\"MacRumors\" /> <br /> '''11 Pro Max''': 3.79 V 15.04 Wh (3969 mAh) Li-ion<ref name=\"MacRumors\" />\n|charging = Fast charging, [[Qi (standard)|Qi]] wireless charging\n|input = \n|display = '''11 Pro:''' {{convert|5.85|in|mm|abbr=on}}, 2436\u00d71125 px <br>'''11 Pro Max:''' {{convert|6.46|in|mm|abbr=on}}, 2688\u00d71242 px <br> '''All models:''' 458 [[Pixel density|ppi]], [[Retina Display|Super Retina XDR]], haptic touch, wide color display ([[DCI-P3]]), true tone display, 800&nbsp;cd/m<sup>2</sup> max. brightness (typical), 1200&nbsp;cd/m<sup>2</sup> max. brightness (HDR), with fingerprint-resistant [[oleophobic]] coating.\n|ext_display  = \n|rear_camera  = 12 MP (1.4 \u03bcm) (1/2.55\u2033) Sony Exmor IMX333-Inspired, triple-lens (one \u0192/2.4 aperture ultra wide angle lens, one \u0192/1.8 wide angle lens, one \u0192/2.0 telephoto lens), [[Image stabilization#Optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]] (on wide-angle and telephoto, not on ultrawide), brighter dual-LED flash, autofocus, IR filter, Burst mode, 6-element lens, 4K video recording at 24, 30 or 60 FPS or 1080p at 30 or 60 FPS, slow-motion video (1080p at 120 FPS or 240 FPS), time-lapse with stabilization, panorama (up to 63 megapixels), portrait mode, portrait lighting, facial recognition, digital image stabilization, stereo audio recording\n|front_camera = 12 MP, \u0192/2.2 aperture, burst mode, exposure control, face detection, auto-HDR, auto image stabilization, Retina flash, 4K video recording at 24, 30 or 60 FPS or 1080p HD at 30 or 60 FPS, slow-motion video (1080p at 120 FPS)\nPortrait Mode, Portrait Lighting and Animoji\n|sound = Stereo speakers with Spatial Audio and [[Dolby Atmos]]\n|other = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling, [[IP Code|IP68]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant), [[USB-C]] to [[Lightning (connector)]], [[GPS]]/[[GNSS]] position, velocity and time.\n|connectivity = [[2G]], [[3G]], [[4G LTE]], Wi\u2011Fi 6 ([[802.11ax]]), Bluetooth 5.0\n|sar = \n|hac = \n|website = {{URL|https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/}}\n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\n\nThe '''iPhone 11 Pro''' and '''iPhone 11 Pro Max''' are [[smartphone]]s designed, developed and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] They are the 13th-generation flagships of the [[iPhone]], succeeding the [[iPhone XS|iPhone XS and iPhone XS Max]], respectively. Apple CEO [[Tim Cook]] unveiled the devices alongside a lower-end model, the [[iPhone 11]], on September 10, 2019, at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] at [[Apple Park]]. Pre-orders began on September 13, 2019, and went on sale on September 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/technology/iphone-11.html|title=Apple iPhone Event: A Rebranded 'Pro' Phone, the Series 5 Watch, a New iPad|website=|url-status=live|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910184003/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/technology/iphone-11.html|archive-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nKey upgrades over the previous devices include the triple-lens rear camera system and the [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic chip]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-and-iphone-11-pro-max-the-most-powerful-and-advanced-smartphones/|title=iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 11 Pro Max: the most powerful and advanced smartphones|website=[[Apple Inc.|Apple Newsroom]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910185030/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-and-iphone-11-pro-max-the-most-powerful-and-advanced-smartphones/|archive-date=2019-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The 11 Pro is Apple's first iPhone to feature a \"pro\" designation, which was previously used only for larger Apple devices, such as the [[iPad Pro]] and [[MacBook Pro]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-a9099841.html|title=IPHONE 11 PRO: RELEASE DATE, PRICE AND DETAILS RELEASED ABOUT NEW PREMIUM APPLE HANDSET|last=Griffin|first=Andrew|website=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911191130/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-a9099841.html|archive-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> and the first to include in the box an 18W fast charger and a [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning]] to [[USB-C]] cable that allows connection to current [[Macintosh|Mac computers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/09/10/iphone-11-pro-max-fast-charger/|title=Apple finally includes a fast charger with the iPhone 11 Pro|website=[[Engadget]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911120444/https://www.engadget.com/2019/09/10/iphone-11-pro-max-fast-charger/|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDetails regarding the smartphone were leaked widely starting several months before the official release, with complete specifications, renderings, and real-life images of the phone being publicized, many of which turned out to be correct, such as advancements in the camera and the continuation of the 'notch' design from the frontal camera featured since the [[iPhone X]].<ref name=\"TechRadar\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-details-features-rumours-latest-update-a9074481.html|title=Apple is about to launch a huge range of new products \u2013 here's what they are|last1=Griffin|first1=Andrew|date=22 August 2019|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 August 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whathifi.com/advice/iphone-11-release-date-price-specs-and-latest-news-for-the-new-iphones|title=iPhone 11: release date, price and leaks for the new iPhone|website=WhatHiFi|language=en|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> However, some leaks turned out to be incorrect, such as the inclusion of bilateral charging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2019/09/23/iphone-11-teardown/|title=iPhone 11 teardown reveals lack of bilateral wireless charging evidence, same logic board as Pro models, more|last=Potuck|first=Michael|date=2019-09-23|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/iphone-11-rumor-roundup-what-you-need-to-know|title=iPhone 11 Rumor Roundup: What You Need to Know|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Official release event invites sent out to press featured layered colored glass elements organized to form the Apple logo, which some reviewers drew similarities to Apple's original logo, suggesting new colors for the phone, and to a patent Apple filed for a new camera design earlier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/iphone-11-launch-date-confirmed-19163964|title=iPhone 11 launch date confirmed as Apple sends out invitation to 'special event'|last=Curtis|first=Sophie|date=2019-09-02|website=mirror|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/58961-iphone-11-apple-event-invite-may-hint-at-the-future-of-smartphone-cameras|title=iPhone 11: Apple Event Invite May Hint at the Future of Smartphone Cameras|last=Brown|first=Mike|website=Inverse|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 11 and 11 Pro were unveiled in a press event at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] in Cupertino, California on September 10, 2019; that was the first Apple event livestreamed on Youtube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-to-stream-iphone-11-pro-event-on-youtube/|title=Apple to stream iPhone 11 Pro event on YouTube|last=Musil|first=Steven|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>  The event featured various other products and services other than the iPhone, including a new Apple Watch, a new iPad, Apple TV+, and Apple Arcade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/everything-apple-announced-at-september-2019-iphone-event/|title=Apple\u2019s September 2019 event: Here\u2019s absolutely everything announced|last=Jansen|first=Mark|work=[[Digital Trends]]|date=2019-09-10|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Pre-orders began on September 13, with the iPhone 11 Pro starting from a base price of $999, and the larger screen Pro Max starting from $1,099. The phones were released on September 20th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-pre-order-iphone-11|title=The iPhone 11 is here \u2014 here's how to order it and the best trade-in deals|last=Chin|first=Monica|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Scan of back of iPhone 11 Pro Max Space Grey.jpg|thumb|top|upright|The back side of the iPhone 11 Pro Max in Space Grey.]]\nThe iPhone 11 Pro is available in Gold, Silver, Space Gray, and Midnight Green, a new color previously not available on iPhones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|title=iPhone 11 Pro \u2013 Technical Specifications \u2013 Apple|access-date=2019-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914011954/https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Similar to the iPhone XS, there is a display cutout at the front that includes the 12MP [[TrueDepth]] camera system and speaker. There is also a new rear camera design with three lenses and a flash in a larger, square-shaped bump, which is the most visible difference compared to the iPhone XS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/apple/149318-iphone-11-colors-colours-pro|title=iPhone 11 colors: All the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro colors available|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911024528/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/apple/149318-iphone-11-colors-colours-pro|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|title=iPhone 11 Pro \u2013 Technical Specifications|website=[[Apple Inc.]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910184851/https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|archive-date=2019-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The Apple logo is now centered on the back of the device with no text, and the glass has a frosted matte finish, unlike the glossy finish found on other glass-backed iPhones.\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max both have an [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic]] processor. Both phones have three internal storage options: 64 GB, 256 GB, and 512 GB, and have 4 GB of RAM.<ref name=\":0\" /> Both models are rated IP68 water and dust resistant, and are resistant for 30 minutes at a depth of 4 meters. The warranty does not cover any water damage to the phone. Also, like previous iPhones, both phones do not have a headphone jack, and come with wired EarPods with a Lightning connector.<ref name=\":2\" /> The iPhone 11 Pro is the first iPhone to be sold with an 18 watt fast charger in the box as opposed to the 5 watt charger in the iPhone XS and previous iPhones.<ref name = \":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3437999/iphone-11-vs-iphone-11-prosspecs-features-colors-price.html|title=iPhone 11 vs 11 Pro|website=[[Macworld]]|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912192731/https://www.macworld.com/article/3437999/iphone-11-vs-iphone-11-prosspecs-features-colors-price.html|archive-date=2019-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Display====\nThe iPhone 11 Pro has a 5.85 inch (marketed as 5.8 inch) [[OLED]] display with a resolution of 2436\u00d71125 pixels (2.7 megapixels at 458 ppi), while the iPhone 11 Pro Max has a 6.46 inch (marketed as 6.5 inch) OLED display with a resolution of 2688\u00d71242 pixels (3.3 megapixels at 458 ppi). Both models feature a [[Retina display|Super Retina XDR Display]] with a 2,000,000:1 contrast ratio and a notch at the top for the TrueDepth camera system and speaker. Apple describes the display as having a \"mini [[Apple Pro Display XDR]]\" on a phone. They also have a True Tone and wide color display supporting HDR with 800 nits of standard brightness and 1200 nits peak brightness if necessary. The screen has an oleophobic coating that is fingerprint-resistant.<ref name=\":2\" /> The display of the iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 11 Pro Max is made by [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20191022000805|title=Samsung increases OLED supply for Apple\u2019s latest iPhones|website=www.theinvestor.co.kr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ewanspence/2019/10/23/apple-iphone-11-success-victory-win-samsung-screen-oled-competition/|title=Apple's iPhone 11 Success Gifts Samsung A Hidden Victory|last=Spence|first=Ewan|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pocketnow.com/apple-increases-iphone-11-pro-panel-orders-from-samsung-display|title=Apple increases iPhone 11 Pro panel orders from Samsung Display|last=Nagy|first=Anton D.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n====Camera====\n\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max both include a triple-lens 12 MP rear camera array. There is one \u0192/2.4 ultra wide angle lens with a 120 degree field of view and 2x optical zoom out, one \u0192/1.8 wide angle lens, and one \u0192/2.0 telephoto lens with 2x optical zoom in. There is a burst mode, image stabilization, [[High dynamic range|HDR]] and a portrait mode with supporting an advanced bokeh effect. The phones support a Portrait Mode supporting depth control and an advanced [[bokeh]] effect. The phone also has an automatic Night Mode allowing the camera to take brighter pictures with reduced noise in low light environments. There is also a redesigned camera app that adds new features such as a scroll wheel for choosing between the different lenses and long-pressing the shutter button to take a video. Apple has also announced a new Deep Fusion feature which will take advantage of AI and machine learning for image processing.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-11-pro/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Roundup|website=[[Macrumors]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911214845/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-11-pro/|archive-date=2019-09-11|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 11 Pro supports [[4K resolution|4K video]] up to 60 fps and 1080p slow motion at up to 240 fps.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, Apple limits the full range of zoom (0.5x -6x) while shooting in 4K @ 60fps to either 0.5x - 1.5x or 1x to 2x depending which lens is selected upon recording. All other resolutions/frame rates support the full zoom set. The phone also features an audio zoom feature which focuses audio on the area that is being zoomed in on.<ref name=\":4\" /> All of the cameras support video although only the wide and telephoto come with [[Image stabilization#Optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Video can be captured with multiple cameras at the same time, through the multi camera recording feature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ubergizmo.com/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-multi-camera-come-to-older-iphones/|title=iPhone 11 Pro's Multi-Camera Video Recording Feature Will Be Coming To Older iPhones|last=PDT|first=Tyler Lee on 09/16/2019 17:09|website=Ubergizmo|language=en|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919134001/https://www.ubergizmo.com/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-multi-camera-come-to-older-iphones/|archive-date=2019-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBoth models also have a 12MP TrueDepth front camera with a \u0192/2.0 aperture. The front camera also supports stabilized 4K video recording up to 60fps.<ref name=\":0\" /> Apple has added slow motion video recording to the front camera in 1080p at up to 120 fps, a feature which Apple refers to as \"slofies\". Similar to previous iPhone models, the TrueDepth system is also used for Face ID and Animoji.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Software===\n{{See also|IOS 13|IOS version history}}\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max initially shipped with the [[iOS 13]] operating system. The phone also comes with [[Siri]], [[Face ID]] (through the TrueDepth camera), [[Apple Pay]], and supports [[Apple Card]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Reception==\nUpon release, the iPhone 11 Pro received positive reviews, with critics highlighting the improvements to the camera, display, and battery, although it was criticized for its similar design to the iPhone XS and the large camera bump, as well as the lack of rumored features such as bilateral wireless charging and USB-C. [[TechRadar]] critics praised the improved camera array, calling it \"clearly the big upgrade\", and also praised the faster [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic]] processor, and the display, while critiquing the design similarities compared to the [[iPhone XS]] including display cutout for the sensor housing, commonly referred to as \u201cthe notch,\u201d and also criticizing the cost.<ref name=\"TechRadar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/reviews/hands-on-iphone-11-max-review|title=Hands on: Hands on: iPhone 11 Pro Max review|last=Beavis|first=Gareth |website=[[TechRadar]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911215147/https://www.techradar.com/reviews/hands-on-iphone-11-max-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/reviews/iphone-11-pro|title=iPhone 11 Pro Hands-on Review|last=Phones|first=Mark Spoonauer 2019-09-11T13:24:44Z|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911022037/https://www.tomsguide.com/reviews/iphone-11-pro|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> Pocket Lint also positively described the camera, the processor, display, and battery, camera design, and lack of bilateral wireless charging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149324-apple-iphone-11-pro-max-review|title=Apple iPhone 11 Pro Max initial review|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911024912/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149324-apple-iphone-11-pro-max-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149323-iphone-11-pro-review|title=Apple iPhone 11 Pro initial review|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911025010/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149323-iphone-11-pro-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Verge]] and T3 positively described the general aspects of the phone, while stating that the 'pro' label may not be fully justified as the phone only helps Apple keep up with the competitors, not surpass them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/10/20857971/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-hands-on-features-photos-video-camera-price|title=iPhone 11 Pro and 11 Pro Max: hands-on with Apple's new flagship phones|last=Bohn|first=Dieter|date=2019-09-10|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911072053/https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/10/20857971/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-hands-on-features-photos-video-camera-price|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.t3.com/news/iphone-11-pro-review-early-verdict-apple-tries-to-go-pro-with-a-triple-lens-camera|title=iPhone 11 Pro review (early verdict): Apple tries to go pro with a triple-lens camera|last=Jones 2019-09-11T10:13:57Z|first=Robert|website=[[T3 (magazine)|T3]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912222739/https://www.t3.com/news/iphone-11-pro-review-early-verdict-apple-tries-to-go-pro-with-a-triple-lens-camera|archive-date=2019-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe device received an overall score of 117 from [[DXOMARK]], ranking it as the second-best smartphone camera on the site tied with the Samsung Galaxy Note 10+. An 11-point improvement over its predecessor, it had a photo score of 124 and a video score of 102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dxomark.com/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-camera-review/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Max camera review|work=[[DXOMARK]]|last=Rehm|first=Lars|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Known issues==\nAn independent radiation test found out that the iPhone 11 Pro emits twice the amount of radiation for safe use.  However, according to the same <I>Spectrum</I> article the FCC was unable to reproduce this, so this test is not conclusive.  <ref>[https://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/telecom/wireless/radio-frequency-exposure-test-iphone-11-pro-double-fcc-limits A Radio Frequency Exposure Test Finds an iPhone 11 Pro Exceeds the FCC's Limit]</ref><ref>[https://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/gadgets/a30857609/iphone-11-pro-radiation/ Your iPhone 11 Pro Emits Twice the Amount of Radiation for Safe Use]</ref>\n\n==Timeline of iPhone models==\n\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n* [[History of iPhone]]\n* [[List of iOS devices]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"0\"></references>{{iOS}}{{Apple hardware since 1998}}{{Apple Inc. hardware}}{{Apple}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/ Official website]\n* [https://www.newmobilereview2020.com/2020/01/iphone-11-pro-review.html IPHONE 11 PRO REVIEW]\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2019]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2019]]\n[[Category:Phones with multiple rear cameras]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:iPhone 11 Pro}}\n{{lowercase title}}\n{{short description|2019 flagship smartphone line produced by Apple Inc.}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n|name = iPhone 11 Pro<br>iPhone 11 Pro Max\n|slogan = * And then there was Pro.\n* Pro Cameras. Pro Display. Pro Performance.\n| modelnumber = '''Pro:''' <br /> A2160<br />A2217 <br />A2215 <br /> '''Pro Max:'''<br />A2161<br />A2220 <br />A2218 \n|logo = IPhone 11 Pro wordmark.svg\n|logosize = 200px\n|image = iPhone 11 Pro Midnight Green.svg\n|caption = iPhone 11 Pro in Midnight Green\n|imagesize = 200px\n|brand = [[Apple Inc.]]\n|serieslabel = [[History of iPhone|Generation]]\n|series = 13th\n|announced = September 10, 2019\n|preorder = September 13, 2019\n|released = {{Start date and age|2019|09|20}}\n|available = {{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=September 20, 2019 <!-- Only based on the apple.com and each countries must mention the iPhone 11 or else it won't be released at this time. -->\n|[[Australia]]\n|[[Austria]]\n|[[Belgium]]\n|[[Canada]]\n|[[China]]\n|[[Czech Republic]]\n|[[Denmark]]\n|[[Finland]]\n|[[France]]\n|[[Germany]]\n|[[Hong Kong]]\n|[[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|[[Italy]]\n|[[Israel]]\n|[[Japan]]\n|[[Mexico]]\n|[[Netherlands]]\n|[[New Zealand]]\n|[[Norway]]\n|[[Poland]]\n|[[Portugal]]\n|[[Russia]]\n|[[Saudi Arabia]]\n|[[Singapore]]\n|[[Slovenia]]\n|[[Spain]]\n|[[Sweden]]\n|[[Switzerland]]\n|[[Taiwan]]\n|[[United Arab Emirates]]\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|[[United States]]}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none;\npadding:0;|title=September 26, 2019\n|[[Israel]]}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none;\npadding:0;|title=September 27, 2019\n|[[Andorra]]\n|[[Bahrain]]\n|[[Brazil]]\n|[[Bulgaria]]\n|[[Croatia]]\n|[[Cyprus]]\n|[[Estonia]]\n|[[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n|[[Hungary]]\n|[[Iceland]]\n|[[India]]\n|[[Kuwait]]\n|[[Latvia]]\n|[[Liechtenstein]]\n|[[Luxembourg]]\n|[[Malaysia]]\n|[[Malta]]\n|[[Monaco]]\n|[[Nigeria]]\n|[[Oman]]\n|[[Qatar]]\n|[[Romania]]\n|[[Slovakia]]}}\n|[[South Africa]]\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=October 18, 2019\n|[[Brazil]]\n|[[Thailand]]}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=October 25, 2019\n|[[Philippines]]\n|[[South Korea]]\n|[[Turkey]]}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=October 26, 2019\n|[[Egypt]]}}\n\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=December 6, 2019\n|[[Indonesia]]}}\n|predecessor = [[iPhone XS|iPhone XS / iPhone XS Max]]\n|successor = \n|related = [[iPhone 11]]\n|type = '''11 Pro:''' [[Smartphone]]<br />'''11 Pro Max:''' [[Phablet]]\n|form = [[Mobile phone form factors#Touchscreen/Slate|Slate]]\n|size = '''11 Pro'''<br>{{convert|144|mm|in|abbr=on}} H <br /> {{convert|71.4|mm|in|abbr=on}} W <br /> {{convert|8.1|mm|in|abbr=on}} D\n<br>'''11 Pro Max''' <br> {{convert|158|mm|in|abbr=on}} H <br /> {{convert|77.8|mm|in|abbr=on}} W <br /> {{convert|8.1|mm|in|abbr=on}} D\n|weight ='''11 Pro'''<br>{{convert|188|g|oz|abbr=on}}<br>'''11 Pro Max'''<br>{{convert|226|g|oz|abbr=on}}\n|os = '''Original:''' [[iOS 13]]<br />'''Current:''' [[iOS 13|iOS 13.4.1]], released {{start date|mf=yes|2020|4|7}}\n|soc = [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic]]\n|cpu = [[Hexa-core]] (2\u00d7 high power Lightning cores at 2.66 GHz + 4\u00d7 low power Thunder cores at 1.82 GHz)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.specenginex.com/spec-apple-iphone11promax.php|title=Apple iPhone 11 Pro Max|publisher=Spec Engine X}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/14859/apple-announces-new-iphone-11-iphone-11-pro-iphone-11-pro-max|title=Apple Announces New iPhone 11, iPhone 11 Pro, & iPhone 11 Pro Max|last=Frumusanu|first=Andrei|website=[[AnandTech]]|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://browser.geekbench.com/ios_devices/64|title=iPhone 11 Pro Geekbench|publisher=geekbench.com|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n|gpu =\n|modem = [[Dual SIM]] with [[eSIM]]<br /> Gigabit-Class LTE Cat.19 with 4x4 MIMO, up to 30 [[LTE frequency bands|LTE bands]]\n|memory = 4 GB LPDDR4X RAM<ref name=\"MacRumors\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2019/09/17/iphone-11-pro-max-battery-mah-4gb-ram-tenaa/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Models Have Up to 25% Larger Batteries and 4GB of RAM Per Reliable TENAA Filings|access-date=2019-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918002119/https://www.macrumors.com/2019/09/17/iphone-11-pro-max-battery-mah-4gb-ram-tenaa/|archive-date=2019-09-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|storage = 64, 256 or 512 [[Gigabytes|GB]]\n|memory_card = None\n|battery = '''11 Pro''': 3.83 V 11.67 Wh (3046 mAh) [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion]]<ref name=\"MacRumors\" /> <br /> '''11 Pro Max''': 3.79 V 15.04 Wh (3969 mAh) Li-ion<ref name=\"MacRumors\" />\n|charging = Fast charging, [[Qi (standard)|Qi]] wireless charging\n|input = \n|display = '''11 Pro:''' {{convert|5.85|in|mm|abbr=on}}, 2436\u00d71125 px <br>'''11 Pro Max:''' {{convert|6.46|in|mm|abbr=on}}, 2688\u00d71242 px <br> '''All models:''' 458 [[Pixel density|ppi]], [[Retina Display|Super Retina XDR]], haptic touch, wide color display ([[DCI-P3]]), true tone display, 800&nbsp;cd/m<sup>2</sup> max. brightness (typical), 1200&nbsp;cd/m<sup>2</sup> max. brightness (HDR), with fingerprint-resistant [[oleophobic]] coating.\n|ext_display  = \n|rear_camera  = 12 MP (1.4 \u03bcm) (1/2.55\u2033) Sony Exmor IMX333-Inspired, triple-lens (one \u0192/2.4 aperture ultra wide angle lens, one \u0192/1.8 wide angle lens, one \u0192/2.0 telephoto lens), [[Image stabilization#Optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]] (on wide-angle and telephoto, not on ultrawide), brighter dual-LED flash, autofocus, IR filter, Burst mode, 6-element lens, 4K video recording at 24, 30 or 60 FPS or 1080p at 30 or 60 FPS, slow-motion video (1080p at 120 FPS or 240 FPS), time-lapse with stabilization, panorama (up to 63 megapixels), portrait mode, portrait lighting, facial recognition, digital image stabilization, stereo audio recording\n|front_camera = 12 MP, \u0192/2.2 aperture, burst mode, exposure control, face detection, auto-HDR, auto image stabilization, Retina flash, 4K video recording at 24, 30 or 60 FPS or 1080p HD at 30 or 60 FPS, slow-motion video (1080p at 120 FPS)\nPortrait Mode, Portrait Lighting and Animoji\n|sound = Stereo speakers with Spatial Audio and [[Dolby Atmos]]\n|other = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling, [[IP Code|IP68]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant), [[USB-C]] to [[Lightning (connector)]], [[GPS]]/[[GNSS]] position, velocity and time.\n|connectivity = [[2G]], [[3G]], [[4G LTE]], Wi\u2011Fi 6 ([[802.11ax]]), Bluetooth 5.0\n|sar = \n|hac = \n|website = {{URL|https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/}}\n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\n\nThe '''iPhone 11 Pro''' and '''iPhone 11 Pro Max''' are [[smartphone]]s designed, developed and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] They are the 13th-generation flagships of the [[iPhone]], succeeding the [[iPhone XS|iPhone XS and iPhone XS Max]], respectively. Apple CEO [[Tim Cook]] unveiled the devices alongside a lower-end model, the [[iPhone 11]], on September 10, 2019, at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] at [[Apple Park]]. Pre-orders began on September 13, 2019, and went on sale on September 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/technology/iphone-11.html|title=Apple iPhone Event: A Rebranded 'Pro' Phone, the Series 5 Watch, a New iPad|website=|url-status=live|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910184003/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/technology/iphone-11.html|archive-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nKey upgrades over the previous devices include the triple-lens rear camera system and the [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic chip]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-and-iphone-11-pro-max-the-most-powerful-and-advanced-smartphones/|title=iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 11 Pro Max: the most powerful and advanced smartphones|website=[[Apple Inc.|Apple Newsroom]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910185030/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-and-iphone-11-pro-max-the-most-powerful-and-advanced-smartphones/|archive-date=2019-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The 11 Pro is Apple's first iPhone to feature a \"pro\" designation, which was previously used only for larger Apple devices, such as the [[iPad Pro]] and [[MacBook Pro]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-a9099841.html|title=IPHONE 11 PRO: RELEASE DATE, PRICE AND DETAILS RELEASED ABOUT NEW PREMIUM APPLE HANDSET|last=Griffin|first=Andrew|website=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911191130/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-a9099841.html|archive-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> and the first to include in the box an 18W fast charger and a [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning]] to [[USB-C]] cable that allows connection to current [[Macintosh|Mac computers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/09/10/iphone-11-pro-max-fast-charger/|title=Apple finally includes a fast charger with the iPhone 11 Pro|website=[[Engadget]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911120444/https://www.engadget.com/2019/09/10/iphone-11-pro-max-fast-charger/|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDetails regarding the smartphone were leaked widely starting several months before the official release, with complete specifications, renderings, and real-life images of the phone being publicized, many of which turned out to be correct, such as advancements in the camera and the continuation of the 'notch' design from the frontal camera featured since the [[iPhone X]].<ref name=\"TechRadar\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-11-pro-apple-release-date-details-features-rumours-latest-update-a9074481.html|title=Apple is about to launch a huge range of new products \u2013 here's what they are|last1=Griffin|first1=Andrew|date=22 August 2019|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 August 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whathifi.com/advice/iphone-11-release-date-price-specs-and-latest-news-for-the-new-iphones|title=iPhone 11: release date, price and leaks for the new iPhone|website=WhatHiFi|language=en|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> However, some leaks turned out to be incorrect, such as the inclusion of bilateral charging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2019/09/23/iphone-11-teardown/|title=iPhone 11 teardown reveals lack of bilateral wireless charging evidence, same logic board as Pro models, more|last=Potuck|first=Michael|date=2019-09-23|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/iphone-11-rumor-roundup-what-you-need-to-know|title=iPhone 11 Rumor Roundup: What You Need to Know|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Official release event invites sent out to press featured layered colored glass elements organized to form the Apple logo, which some reviewers drew similarities to Apple's original logo, suggesting new colors for the phone, and to a patent Apple filed for a new camera design earlier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/iphone-11-launch-date-confirmed-19163964|title=iPhone 11 launch date confirmed as Apple sends out invitation to 'special event'|last=Curtis|first=Sophie|date=2019-09-02|website=mirror|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/58961-iphone-11-apple-event-invite-may-hint-at-the-future-of-smartphone-cameras|title=iPhone 11: Apple Event Invite May Hint at the Future of Smartphone Cameras|last=Brown|first=Mike|website=Inverse|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 11 and 11 Pro were unveiled in a press event at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] in Cupertino, California on September 10, 2019; that was the first Apple event livestreamed on Youtube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-to-stream-iphone-11-pro-event-on-youtube/|title=Apple to stream iPhone 11 Pro event on YouTube|last=Musil|first=Steven|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>  The event featured various other products and services other than the iPhone, including a new Apple Watch, a new iPad, Apple TV+, and Apple Arcade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/everything-apple-announced-at-september-2019-iphone-event/|title=Apple\u2019s September 2019 event: Here\u2019s absolutely everything announced|last=Jansen|first=Mark|work=[[Digital Trends]]|date=2019-09-10|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Pre-orders began on September 13, with the iPhone 11 Pro starting from a base price of $999, and the larger screen Pro Max starting from $1,099. The phones were released on September 20th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-pre-order-iphone-11|title=The iPhone 11 is here \u2014 here's how to order it and the best trade-in deals|last=Chin|first=Monica|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Scan of back of iPhone 11 Pro Max Space Grey.jpg|thumb|top|upright|The back side of the iPhone 11 Pro Max in Space Grey.]]\nThe iPhone 11 Pro is available in Gold, Silver, Space Gray, and Midnight Green, a new color previously not available on iPhones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|title=iPhone 11 Pro \u2013 Technical Specifications \u2013 Apple|access-date=2019-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914011954/https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Similar to the iPhone XS, there is a display cutout at the front that includes the 12MP [[TrueDepth]] camera system and speaker. There is also a new rear camera design with three lenses and a flash in a larger, square-shaped bump, which is the most visible difference compared to the iPhone XS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/apple/149318-iphone-11-colors-colours-pro|title=iPhone 11 colors: All the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro colors available|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911024528/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/apple/149318-iphone-11-colors-colours-pro|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|title=iPhone 11 Pro \u2013 Technical Specifications|website=[[Apple Inc.]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910184851/https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/specs/|archive-date=2019-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The Apple logo is now centered on the back of the device with no text, and the glass has a frosted matte finish, unlike the glossy finish found on other glass-backed iPhones.\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max both have an [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic]] processor. Both phones have three internal storage options: 64 GB, 256 GB, and 512 GB, and have 4 GB of RAM.<ref name=\":0\" /> Both models are rated IP68 water and dust resistant, and are resistant for 30 minutes at a depth of 4 meters. The warranty does not cover any water damage to the phone. Also, like previous iPhones, both phones do not have a headphone jack, and come with wired EarPods with a Lightning connector.<ref name=\":2\" /> The iPhone 11 Pro is the first iPhone to be sold with an 18 watt fast charger in the box as opposed to the 5 watt charger in the iPhone XS and previous iPhones.<ref name = \":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3437999/iphone-11-vs-iphone-11-prosspecs-features-colors-price.html|title=iPhone 11 vs 11 Pro|website=[[Macworld]]|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912192731/https://www.macworld.com/article/3437999/iphone-11-vs-iphone-11-prosspecs-features-colors-price.html|archive-date=2019-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Display====\nThe iPhone 11 Pro has a 5.85 inch (marketed as 5.8 inch) [[OLED]] display with a resolution of 2436\u00d71125 pixels (2.7 megapixels at 458 ppi), while the iPhone 11 Pro Max has a 6.46 inch (marketed as 6.5 inch) OLED display with a resolution of 2688\u00d71242 pixels (3.3 megapixels at 458 ppi). Both models feature a [[Retina display|Super Retina XDR Display]] with a 2,000,000:1 contrast ratio and a notch at the top for the TrueDepth camera system and speaker. Apple describes the display as having a \"mini [[Apple Pro Display XDR]]\" on a phone. They also have a True Tone and wide color display supporting HDR with 800 nits of standard brightness and 1200 nits peak brightness if necessary. The screen has an oleophobic coating that is fingerprint-resistant.<ref name=\":2\" /> The display of the iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 11 Pro Max is made by [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20191022000805|title=Samsung increases OLED supply for Apple\u2019s latest iPhones|website=www.theinvestor.co.kr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ewanspence/2019/10/23/apple-iphone-11-success-victory-win-samsung-screen-oled-competition/|title=Apple's iPhone 11 Success Gifts Samsung A Hidden Victory|last=Spence|first=Ewan|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pocketnow.com/apple-increases-iphone-11-pro-panel-orders-from-samsung-display|title=Apple increases iPhone 11 Pro panel orders from Samsung Display|last=Nagy|first=Anton D.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n====Camera====\n\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max both include a triple-lens 12 MP rear camera array. There is one \u0192/2.4 ultra wide angle lens with a 120 degree field of view and 2x optical zoom out, one \u0192/1.8 wide angle lens, and one \u0192/2.0 telephoto lens with 2x optical zoom in. There is a burst mode, image stabilization, [[High dynamic range|HDR]] and a portrait mode with supporting an advanced bokeh effect. The phones support a Portrait Mode supporting depth control and an advanced [[bokeh]] effect. The phone also has an automatic Night Mode allowing the camera to take brighter pictures with reduced noise in low light environments. There is also a redesigned camera app that adds new features such as a scroll wheel for choosing between the different lenses and long-pressing the shutter button to take a video. Apple has also announced a new Deep Fusion feature which will take advantage of AI and machine learning for image processing.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-11-pro/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Roundup|website=[[Macrumors]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911214845/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-11-pro/|archive-date=2019-09-11|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone 11 Pro supports [[4K resolution|4K video]] up to 60 fps and 1080p slow motion at up to 240 fps.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, Apple limits the full range of zoom (0.5x -6x) while shooting in 4K @ 60fps to either 0.5x - 1.5x or 1x to 2x depending which lens is selected upon recording. All other resolutions/frame rates support the full zoom set. The phone also features an audio zoom feature which focuses audio on the area that is being zoomed in on.<ref name=\":4\" /> All of the cameras support video although only the wide and telephoto come with [[Image stabilization#Optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Video can be captured with multiple cameras at the same time, through the multi camera recording feature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ubergizmo.com/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-multi-camera-come-to-older-iphones/|title=iPhone 11 Pro's Multi-Camera Video Recording Feature Will Be Coming To Older iPhones|last=PDT|first=Tyler Lee on 09/16/2019 17:09|website=Ubergizmo|language=en|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919134001/https://www.ubergizmo.com/2019/09/iphone-11-pro-multi-camera-come-to-older-iphones/|archive-date=2019-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBoth models also have a 12MP TrueDepth front camera with a \u0192/2.0 aperture. The front camera also supports stabilized 4K video recording up to 60fps.<ref name=\":0\" /> Apple has added slow motion video recording to the front camera in 1080p at up to 120 fps, a feature which Apple refers to as \"slofies\". Similar to previous iPhone models, the TrueDepth system is also used for Face ID and Animoji.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Software===\n{{See also|IOS 13|IOS version history}}\nThe iPhone 11 Pro and Pro Max initially shipped with the [[iOS 13]] operating system. The phone also comes with [[Siri]], [[Face ID]] (through the TrueDepth camera), [[Apple Pay]], and supports [[Apple Card]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Reception==\nUpon release, the iPhone 11 Pro received generally positive reviews, with critics highlighting the improvements to the camera, display, and battery, although it was criticized for its similar design to the iPhone XS and the large camera bump, as well as the lack of rumored features such as bilateral wireless charging and USB-C. [[TechRadar]] critics praised the improved camera array, calling it \"clearly the big upgrade\", and also praised the faster [[Apple A13|A13 Bionic]] processor, and the display, while critiquing the design similarities compared to the [[iPhone XS]] including display cutout for the sensor housing, commonly referred to as \u201cthe notch,\u201d and also criticizing the cost.<ref name=\"TechRadar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/reviews/hands-on-iphone-11-max-review|title=Hands on: Hands on: iPhone 11 Pro Max review|last=Beavis|first=Gareth |website=[[TechRadar]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911215147/https://www.techradar.com/reviews/hands-on-iphone-11-max-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/reviews/iphone-11-pro|title=iPhone 11 Pro Hands-on Review|last=Phones|first=Mark Spoonauer 2019-09-11T13:24:44Z|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911022037/https://www.tomsguide.com/reviews/iphone-11-pro|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> Pocket Lint also positively described the camera, the processor, display, and battery, camera design, and lack of bilateral wireless charging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149324-apple-iphone-11-pro-max-review|title=Apple iPhone 11 Pro Max initial review|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911024912/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149324-apple-iphone-11-pro-max-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149323-iphone-11-pro-review|title=Apple iPhone 11 Pro initial review|last=Pocket-lint|date=2019-09-11|website=Pocket-lint|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911025010/https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/reviews/apple/149323-iphone-11-pro-review|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Verge]] and T3 positively described the general aspects of the phone, while stating that the 'pro' label may not be fully justified as the phone only helps Apple keep up with the competitors, not surpass them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/10/20857971/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-hands-on-features-photos-video-camera-price|title=iPhone 11 Pro and 11 Pro Max: hands-on with Apple's new flagship phones|last=Bohn|first=Dieter|date=2019-09-10|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911072053/https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/10/20857971/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-hands-on-features-photos-video-camera-price|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.t3.com/news/iphone-11-pro-review-early-verdict-apple-tries-to-go-pro-with-a-triple-lens-camera|title=iPhone 11 Pro review (early verdict): Apple tries to go pro with a triple-lens camera|last=Jones 2019-09-11T10:13:57Z|first=Robert|website=[[T3 (magazine)|T3]]|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912222739/https://www.t3.com/news/iphone-11-pro-review-early-verdict-apple-tries-to-go-pro-with-a-triple-lens-camera|archive-date=2019-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe device received an overall score of 117 from [[DXOMARK]], ranking it as the second-best smartphone camera on the site tied with the Samsung Galaxy Note 10+. An 11-point improvement over its predecessor, it had a photo score of 124 and a video score of 102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dxomark.com/apple-iphone-11-pro-max-camera-review/|title=iPhone 11 Pro Max camera review|work=[[DXOMARK]]|last=Rehm|first=Lars|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Known issues==\nAn independent radiation test found out that the iPhone 11 Pro emits twice the amount of radiation for safe use.  However, according to the same <I>Spectrum</I> article the FCC was unable to reproduce this, so this test is not conclusive.  <ref>[https://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/telecom/wireless/radio-frequency-exposure-test-iphone-11-pro-double-fcc-limits A Radio Frequency Exposure Test Finds an iPhone 11 Pro Exceeds the FCC's Limit]</ref><ref>[https://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/gadgets/a30857609/iphone-11-pro-radiation/ Your iPhone 11 Pro Emits Twice the Amount of Radiation for Safe Use]</ref>\n\n==Timeline of iPhone models==\n\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n* [[History of iPhone]]\n* [[List of iOS devices]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"0\"></references>{{iOS}}{{Apple hardware since 1998}}{{Apple Inc. hardware}}{{Apple}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.apple.com/iphone-11-pro/ Official website]\n* [https://www.newmobilereview2020.com/2020/01/iphone-11-pro-review.html IPHONE 11 PRO REVIEW]\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2019]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2019]]\n[[Category:Phones with multiple rear cameras]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1004:b029:dcab:d5c3:ba3e:3980:93d0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReception)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_11_Pro"}
{"title_page": "Bamboo and wooden slips", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=March 2013}}\n[[File:Manuscript from Shanghai Museum 1.jpg|170px|thumb|upright|A sample of the [[Shanghai Museum bamboo slips]] (c. 300 BC), recording part of a commentary on the ''[[Classic of Poetry]]'']]\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|t=\u7c21\u7258\n|s=\u7b80\u724d\n|l=\"Bamboo strips and wooden slips\"\n|p=ji\u01cend\u00fa\n|w=chien<sup>3</sup>-tu<sup>2</sup>\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|j|ian|3|d|u|2}}\n|j=gaan<sup>2</sup>-duk<sup>6</sup>\n|y=g\u00e1an-duhk\n|tl=k\u00e1n-to\u030dk\n|mc= /k\u02e0\u025bn<sup>X</sup>duk\u031a/\n}}\n[[File:Bamboo book - binding - UCR.jpg|thumb|right|An 18th-century edition of ''[[The Art of War]]'' made with bamboo strips]]\n\n'''Bamboo and wooden slips''' ({{zh|s=\u7b80\u724d|p=ji\u01cend\u00fa}}) were the main media for writing documents in China before the widespread [[history of paper|introduction of paper]] during the first two centuries AD. (Silk was occasionally used, for example in the [[Chu Silk Manuscript]], but was prohibitively expensive for most documents.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cn.nytimes.com/culture/20180621/ancient-chinese-manuscript-sackler/zh-hant/|title=\u5beb\u65bc2300\u5e74\u524d\u7684\u300a\u695a\u5e1b\u66f8\u300b\u5982\u4f55\u6d41\u843d\u5230\u4e86\u7f8e\u570b\uff1f|last=\u5f35\u5f65|first=|date=2018-06-21|website=[[The New York Times]]|language=zh-cmn-hant|trans-title=How did the Chu Silk Manuscript, written 2,300 years ago, get to the United States?|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest surviving examples of wood or bamboo slips date from the 5th century BC during the [[Warring States period]]. However, references in earlier texts surviving on other media make it clear that some precursor of these Warring States period bamboo slips was in use as early as the late [[Shang dynasty|Shang]] period (from about 1250 BC). Bamboo or wooden strips were the standard writing material during the Han dynasty and excavated examples have been found in abundance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Loewe|first=Michael|chapter=Wood and bamboo administrative documents of the Han period|editor=Edward L. Shaughnessy| title=New Sources of Early Chinese History|publisher=Society for the Study of Early China|year=1997|pages=161\u2013192|isbn=1-55729-058-X}}</ref> Subsequently, the invention of [[History of paper|paper]] by [[Cai Lun]] during the [[Science and technology of the Han dynasty|Han dynasty]] began to displace bamboo and wooden strips from mainstream uses, and by the 4th century AD bamboo had been largely abandoned as a medium for writing in China.\n\nThe long, narrow strips of wood or bamboo typically carry a single column of brush-written text each, with space for several tens of visually complex ancient Chinese characters. Each strip of wood or bamboo is said to be as long as a chopstick and as wide as two. For longer texts, many slips were sewn together used to make a kind of folding book.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Encyclopedia of China: History and Culture |last=Perkins |first=Dorothy |publisher=Routledge |year=1998 |isbn=978-1579581107 |pages=24}}</ref>\n\nThe custom of interring books made of the durable bamboo strips in royal tombs has preserved many works in their original form through the centuries. An important early find was the [[Jizhong discovery]] in 279 AD of a tomb of a king of [[Wei (state)|Wei]], though the original recovered strips have since disappeared. Several caches of great importance have been found in recent years.\n\n==Major collections==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Collection\n! scope=\"col\" | Province\n! scope=\"col\" | Found\n! scope=\"col\" | Period\n|-\n| Mozuizi (\u78e8\u5634\u5b50)|| Gansu || 1959 || Eastern Han\n|-\n| [[Yinqueshan Han Slips]] || Shandong || 1972 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Shuihudi Qin bamboo texts]] || Hubei || 1975 || Qin\n|-\n| [[Shuanggudui]] || Anhui || 1977 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Zhangjiashan Han bamboo texts]] || Hubei || 1983 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Fangmatan]] || Gansu || 1986 || late Warring States ([[Qin (state)|Qin]])\n|-\n| [[Guodian Chu Slips]] || Hubei || 1993 || mid to late Warring States\n|-\n| [[Shanghai Museum bamboo slips]] || Hubei || 1994 || mid to late Warring States\n|-\n| [[Zoumalou bamboo slips]] || Hunan || 1996 || Three Kingdoms ([[Eastern Wu]])\n|-\n| Yinwan (\u5c39\u7063) || Jiangsu || 1997 || Western Han<ref>{{cite web|last=Loewe |first=Michael |title=The Administrative Documents from Yinwan: A Summary of Certain Issues Raised |url=http://ealc.uchicago.edu/earlychina/research_resources/notes/yinwan.htm |date=November 2001 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403175412/http://ealc.uchicago.edu/earlychina/research_resources/notes/yinwan.htm |archivedate=2012-04-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Qin Slips of Liye]]|| Hunan || 2002 || Qin dynasty\n|-\n| [[Tsinghua Bamboo Slips]] || Hunan or Hubei? || 2008 || mid to late Warring States\n|}\n\nThe Shanghai Museum corpus was purchased in Hong Kong the year after the Guodian tomb was excavated, and is believed to have been taken by tomb robbers from a tomb in the same area. The Tsinghua collection was donated by an alumnus who purchased it through auction, with no indication of its origin. The others are archaeologically excavated.\n\n==Accoutrements==\nOne accoutrement used when writing on bamboo slips was a small knife which would be used to scrape away mistakes and make amendments. Decorated knives became a symbol of office for some officials indicating their power to amend and change records and edicts.\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat|Bamboo slips}}\n* [[Bamboo Annals]]\n* [[Bamboo tally]]\n* [[Chu Silk Manuscript]]\n* [[Mawangdui Silk Texts]]\n* [[Oracle bone]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Writing}}\n\n[[Category:Bamboo and wooden slips| ]]\n[[Category:Chinese inventions]]\n[[Category:Writing media]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=March 2013}}\n[[File:Manuscript from Shanghai Museum 1.jpg|170px|thumb|upright|A sample of the [[Shanghai Museum bamboo slips]] (c. 300 BC), recording part of a commentary on the ''[[Classic of Poetry]]'']]\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|t=\u7c21\u7258\n|s=\u7b80\u724d\n|l=\"Bamboo strips and wooden slips\"\n|p=ji\u01cend\u00fa\n|w=chien<sup>3</sup>-tu<sup>2</sup>\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|j|ian|3|d|u|2}}\n|j=gaan<sup>2</sup>-duk<sup>6</sup>\n|y=g\u00e1an-duhk\n|tl=k\u00e1n-to\u030dk\n|mc= /k\u02e0\u025bn<sup>X</sup>duk\u031a/\n}}\n[[File:Bamboo book - binding - UCR.jpg|thumb|right|An 18th-century edition of ''[[The Art of War]]'' made with bamboo strips]]\n\n'''Bamboo and wooden slips''' ({{zh|s=\u7b80\u724d|p=ji\u01cend\u00fa}}) were the main media for writing documents in China before the widespread [[history of paper|introduction of paper]] during the first two centuries AD. (Silk was occasionally used, for example in the [[Chu Silk Manuscript]], but was prohibitively expensive for most documents.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cn.nytimes.com/culture/20180621/ancient-chinese-manuscript-sackler/zh-hant/|title=\u5beb\u65bc2300\u5e74\u524d\u7684\u300a\u695a\u5e1b\u66f8\u300b\u5982\u4f55\u6d41\u843d\u5230\u4e86\u7f8e\u570b\uff1f|last=\u5f35\u5f65|first=|date=2018-06-21|website=[[New York Times]]|language=zh-cmn-hant|trans-title=How did the Chu Silk Manuscript, written 2,300 years ago, get to the United States?|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest surviving examples of wood or bamboo slips date from the 5th century BC during the [[Warring States period]]. However, references in earlier texts surviving on other media make it clear that some precursor of these Warring States period bamboo slips was in use as early as the late [[Shang dynasty|Shang]] period (from about 1250 BC). Bamboo or wooden strips were the standard writing material during the Han dynasty and excavated examples have been found in abundance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Loewe|first=Michael|chapter=Wood and bamboo administrative documents of the Han period|editor=Edward L. Shaughnessy| title=New Sources of Early Chinese History|publisher=Society for the Study of Early China|year=1997|pages=161\u2013192|isbn=1-55729-058-X}}</ref> Subsequently, the invention of [[History of paper|paper]] by [[Cai Lun]] during the [[Science and technology of the Han dynasty|Han dynasty]] began to displace bamboo and wooden strips from mainstream uses, and by the 4th century AD bamboo had been largely abandoned as a medium for writing in China.\n\nThe long, narrow strips of wood or bamboo typically carry a single column of brush-written text each, with space for several tens of visually complex ancient Chinese characters. Each strip of wood or bamboo is said to be as long as a chopstick and as wide as two. For longer texts, many slips were sewn together used to make a kind of folding book.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Encyclopedia of China: History and Culture |last=Perkins |first=Dorothy |publisher=Routledge |year=1998 |isbn=978-1579581107 |pages=24}}</ref>\n\nThe custom of interring books made of the durable bamboo strips in royal tombs has preserved many works in their original form through the centuries. An important early find was the [[Jizhong discovery]] in 279 AD of a tomb of a king of [[Wei (state)|Wei]], though the original recovered strips have since disappeared. Several caches of great importance have been found in recent years.\n\n==Major collections==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Collection\n! scope=\"col\" | Province\n! scope=\"col\" | Found\n! scope=\"col\" | Period\n|-\n| Mozuizi (\u78e8\u5634\u5b50)|| Gansu || 1959 || Eastern Han\n|-\n| [[Yinqueshan Han Slips]] || Shandong || 1972 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Shuihudi Qin bamboo texts]] || Hubei || 1975 || Qin\n|-\n| [[Shuanggudui]] || Anhui || 1977 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Zhangjiashan Han bamboo texts]] || Hubei || 1983 || Western Han\n|-\n| [[Fangmatan]] || Gansu || 1986 || late Warring States ([[Qin (state)|Qin]])\n|-\n| [