{"title_page": "Brevard Mall", "text_new": "'''Brevard Mall''' was an enclosed shopping mall in [[Melbourne, Florida]], United States. A small, two-anchor mall, it was the first mall in [[Brevard County, Florida]], and was the first mall built by [[The DeBartolo Corporation|The Edward J. DeBartolo Corporation]] in Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karel|first=Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48366000/|title=Did Shopping Center Deal Jell|date=October 5, 1961|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently, the mall has been converted into an office complex called the Florida Business Center, with tenants including [[Percepta]], [[Collins Aerospace]], and [[IHeartMedia]].\n\n== History ==\nDeveloped by the Edward J. DeBartolo Corporation, plans for the mall were announced in 1961, anchored by a two-level [[Montgomery Ward]] and [[J. C. Penney]], with space for 24 stores in between, at that time to include a [[McCrory Stores|McCrory's 5 & 10]], a [[Food Fair]], a savings and loan, two women's wear stores, two shoe stores, a men's shop, a restaurant, a child's clothing store, and a jewelry store.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karel|first=Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48361157/|title=Bigger Shopping Center?|date=September 15, 1961|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Construction for the mall began in early 1962, on a 32-acre site considered part of the [[Orlando Melbourne International Airport|Melbourne Airport]], and previously housing a television & appliance store, and a miniature golf course. At this time, an opening date of Fall 1962 was announced, as well as new tenants including [[Eckerd Drugs]], [[Winn-Dixie]], and [[Kinney Shoes]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pyle|first=Homer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48366979/|title=Mall Sets Opening In Fall|date=February 3, 1962|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48367100/|title=Construction Set On Brevard Mall|date=February 2, 1962|work=Orlando Evening Star|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Montgomery Ward announced a March 27, 1963 opening by January that year, with its auto center opening ahead of the main store, on March 18, 1963.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Robshaw|first=Walt|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48368110/|title=New Store Opening March 27|date=January 24, 1963|work=Brevard Star|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48368251/|title=MW Auto Store Set To Open|date=March 17, 1963|work=Brevard Sentinel|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The mall opened as planned on March 27, 1963, with a mix of national and local tenants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48369369/|title=Mall Shops To Open Doors Today|date=March 27, 1963|work=Brevard Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe mall's Montgomery Ward was converted to [[Jefferson Ward]] in 1980, in a $2 million renovation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hogan|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48369934/|title=Brevard Retail Centers Undergo Expansion, Change|date=April 20, 1980|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, plans were announced to greatly expand the mall; A joint venture by owners Jim Wilson & Associates with [[Homart Development Company]] and Mel Sembler Associates, it would add 125 stores to the mall, connecting it to an existing [[Sears]] and adding [[Ivey's]] as a fourth anchor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hogan|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46655618/florida-today/|title=Two malls may battle for Melbourne|date=February 7, 1981|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Plans collapsed however in March 1981, when anchor [[J. C. Penney]] announced it would not be renewing it's lease, set to run out in 1983, in order to move to the new [[Melbourne Square (mall)|Melbourne Square Mall]], followed shortly by Ivey's.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cone|first=Marla|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46655744/|title=J.C. Penney move ends 2-mall battle|date=March 12, 1981|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> JCPenney was re-tenanted in late 1984, when HomeOwners Warehouse, a subsidiary of [[Service Merchandise]], renovated and opened in the space.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hodges|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48370889/|title=Brevard Mall welcomes HomeOwners Warehouse|date=December 14, 1984|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jefferson Ward anchor folded with the rest of the chain in 1986, and remained vacant until 1988, when Montgomery Ward returned to the mall alongside a $1.25 million renovation by new owners J.J. Gumberg Co.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carey|first=Chris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48370045/|title=Putting new faces on old shopping centers|date=April 3, 1988|work=The Orlando Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[TJ Maxx]] was announced in 1987, taking over the former Winn-Dixie space as well as a few smaller tenants nearby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48371603/|title=TJ Maxx plans store in Melbourne|date=November 18, 1987|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carey|first=Chris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48371688/|title=Ward leads mall recovery|date=July 12, 1987|work=The Orlando Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, as part of their [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11 Bankruptcy]] filing, Montgomery Ward closed 48 stores, including the location at the Brevard Mall, which closed in August.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372115/|title=Montgomery Ward closings could leave 3,800 jobless|date=October 11, 1997|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Also in 1997, the mall underwent renovations into the \"Florida Marketplace\", a mixed-use center including offices, retail, and a convention center space in the former Montgomery Ward space.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Worley|first=Dwight|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372431/|title=Mall launches new look in January|date=December 5, 1997|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372509/|title=Panel ponders new name for airport|date=February 19, 1998|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Melbourne, Florida]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Defunct shopping malls in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brevard Mall''' was an enclosed shopping mall in [[Melbourne, Florida]], United States. A small, two-anchor mall, it was the first mall in [[Brevard County, Florida]], and was the first mall built by [[The DeBartolo Corporation|The Edward J. DeBartolo Corporation]] in Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karel|first=Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48366000/|title=Did Shopping Center Deal Jell|date=October 5, 1961|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently, the mall has been converted into an office complex called the Florida Business Center, with tenants including [[Percepta]], [[Collins Aerospace]], and [[IHeartMedia]].\n\n== History ==\nDeveloped by the Edward J. DeBartolo Corporation, plans for the mall were announced in 1961, anchored by a two-level [[Montgomery Ward]] and [[J. C. Penney]], with space for 24 stores in between, at that time to include a [[McCrory Stores|McCrory's 5 & 10]], a [[Food Fair]], a savings and loan, two women's wear stores, two shoe stores, a men's shop, a restaurant, a child's clothing store, and a jewelry store.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karel|first=Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48361157/|title=Bigger Shopping Center?|date=September 15, 1961|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Construction for the mall began in early 1962, on a 32-acre site considered part of the [[Orlando Melbourne International Airport|Melbourne Airport]], and previously housing a television & appliance store, and a miniature golf course. At this time, an opening date of Fall 1962 was announced, as well as new tenants including [[Eckerd Drugs]], [[Winn-Dixie]], and [[Kinney Shoes]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pyle|first=Homer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48366979/|title=Mall Sets Opening In Fall|date=February 3, 1962|work=The Miami Herald|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48367100/|title=Construction Set On Brevard Mall|date=February 2, 1962|work=Orlando Evening Star|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Montgomery Ward announced a March 27, 1963 opening by January that year, with it's auto center opening ahead of the main store, on March 18th, 1963.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Robshaw|first=Walt|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48368110/|title=New Store Opening March 27|date=January 24, 1963|work=Brevard Star|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48368251/|title=MW Auto Store Set To Open|date=March 17, 1963|work=Brevard Sentinel|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The mall opened as planned on March 27, 1963, with a mix of national and local tenants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48369369/|title=Mall Shops To Open Doors Today|date=March 27, 1963|work=Brevard Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe mall's Montgomery Ward was converted to [[Jefferson Ward]] in 1980, in a $2 million renovation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hogan|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48369934/|title=Brevard Retail Centers Undergo Expansion, Change|date=April 20, 1980|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, plans were announced to greatly expand the mall; A joint venture by owners Jim Wilson & Associates with [[Homart Development Company]] and Mel Sembler Associates, it would add 125 stores to the mall, connecting it to an existing [[Sears]] and adding [[Ivey's]] as a fourth anchor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hogan|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46655618/florida-today/|title=Two malls may battle for Melbourne|date=February 7, 1981|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Plans collapsed however in March 1981, when anchor [[J. C. Penney]] announced it would not be renewing it's lease, set to run out in 1983, in order to move to the new [[Melbourne Square (mall)|Melbourne Square Mall]], followed shortly by Ivey's.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cone|first=Marla|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46655744/|title=J.C. Penney move ends 2-mall battle|date=March 12, 1981|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> JCPenney was re-tenanted in late 1984, when HomeOwners Warehouse, a subsidiary of [[Service Merchandise]], renovated and opened in the space.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hodges|first=Dave|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48370889/|title=Brevard Mall welcomes HomeOwners Warehouse|date=December 14, 1984|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jefferson Ward anchor folded with the rest of the chain in 1986, and remained vacant until 1988, when Montgomery Ward returned to the mall alongside a $1.25 million renovation by new owners J.J. Gumberg Co.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carey|first=Chris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48370045/|title=Putting new faces on old shopping centers|date=April 3, 1988|work=The Orlando Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[TJ Maxx]] was announced in 1987, taking over the former Winn-Dixie space as well as a few smaller tenants nearby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48371603/|title=TJ Maxx plans store in Melbourne|date=November 18, 1987|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carey|first=Chris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48371688/|title=Ward leads mall recovery|date=July 12, 1987|work=The Orlando Sentinel|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, as part of their [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11 Bankruptcy]] filing, Montgomery Ward closed 48 stores, including the location at the Brevard Mall, which closed in August.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372115/|title=Montgomery Ward closings could leave 3,800 jobless|date=October 11, 1997|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Also in 1997, the mall underwent renovations into the \"Florida Marketplace\", a mixed-use center including offices, retail, and a convention center space in the former Montgomery Ward space.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Worley|first=Dwight|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372431/|title=Mall launches new look in January|date=December 5, 1997|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48372509/|title=Panel ponders new name for airport|date=February 19, 1998|work=Florida Today|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Melbourne, Florida]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Defunct shopping malls in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: it's \u2192 its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brevard_Mall"}
{"title_page": "Bambang Widjojanto", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Bambang Widjojanto\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> Bambang Widjojanto.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Portrait as member of KPK\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|08|18}}\n| birth_place = Jakarta\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indonesian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Human rights work\n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Bambang Widjojanto''' (born 18&nbsp;October 1959) is an Indonesian human rights activist. He is the co-founder of the Indonesian Legal Aid Foundation and a \"leading advocate for the rights of the indigenous peoples of West Papua\".<ref name=RFK /> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', his work for indigenous peoples made him \"the target of repeated threats and detentions by the Indonesian government\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/08/news/08iht-topic_1.html |title=Asian Topics : Around Asia |date=8 October 1993 |author=Arthur Higbee |work=The New York Times |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBambang was born in Jakarta on 18&nbsp;October 1959. He did his undergraduate degree at Jayabaya University, then became a lawyer. By 1986 he was active with legal aid foundations throughout the country. Together with [[Munir Said Thalib]] he helped establish the human rights organisation KontraS; Wijojanto was also involved with the establishment of the Consortium for National Law Reform and the Indonesian Corruption Watch.<ref name=\"KPK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kpk.go.id/modules/commissioners/ |title=Bambang Widjojanto |language=Indonesian |publisher=Corruption Eradication Commission |archivedate=7 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68yOi2mE6?url=http://www.kpk.go.id/modules/commissioners/ |accessdate=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Human rights work ==\nIn 1993, he won the [[Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award]]. Following the award, the [[Robert F. Kennedy Center for Justice and Human Rights]] formed a team of legal experts to assist Bambang in his work.<ref name=RFK>{{cite web |url=http://rfkcenter.org/1993-bambang-widjojanto-indonesia |title=1993: Bambang Widjojanto, Indonesia |publisher=Robert F. Kennedy Center for Justice and Human Rights |accessdate=6 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520232419/http://rfkcenter.org/1993-bambang-widjojanto-indonesia |archive-date=20 May 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he succeeded [[Adnan Buyung Nasution]] as the head of the [[Legal Aid Institute (Jakarta)|Legal Aid Institute]] (LBH, ''Lembaga Bantuan Hukum''), a \"central organisation within the pro-democracy movement\". Bambang's replacement of Nasution caused a schism within the group, and several activists left to form the rival Indonesian Legal Aid and Human Rights Association.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=uV-LLHSQNY0C&pg=PA100&dq=Bambang+Widjojanto#v=onepage&q=Bambang%20Widjojanto&f=false |title=Indonesia and the \"Third Wave of Democratization\": The Indonesian Pro-Democracy Movement in a Changing World |last=Uhlin |first=Anders |year=1997 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0312173838 |page=100 |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The following year, he defended [[Muchtar Pakpahan]], a labour union leader arrested by the government of President [[Suharto]]. The government then attempted to pressure Bambang to testify against his client.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/21/opinion/indonesia-s-cynical-crackdown.html |title=Indonesia's Cynical Crackdown |date=21 January 1997 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nBambang received a master's degree in law from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] in London. In 2005 he graduated from [[Padjadjaran University]] in [[Bandung]] with a master's degree in [[business law]]; this was followed by a doctorate from the same university in 2009. During this period he was on several special commissions, working with the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]] and the prosecutor general's office.<ref name=\"KPK\"/>\n\n== Corruption Eradication Commission candidacies ==\nIn 2010, Bambang was one of two finalists to head Indonesia's [[Corruption Eradication Commission]] (KPK), along with [[Muhammad Busyro Muqoddas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/two-left-in-race-for-anti-graft-job/story-e6frg6so-1225911068199 |title=Two left in race for anti-graft job |author=Peter Alford |date=28 August 2010 |work=The Australian |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Busyro was eventually selected for the position, though President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono offered Bambang a \"consolation post\" heading the Attorney General's Office Commission to reform the [[Indonesian National Police|National Police]] as well as the Attorney General's Office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2010/11/26/sby-offers-consolation-post-bambang-widjojanto.html |title=SBY offers consolation post to Bambang Widjojanto |date=26 November 2010 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Bambang ran again for the office the following year;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/20/noted-activist-gives-kpk-chair-a-second-shot.html |title=Noted activist gives KPK chair a second shot |author=Jakarta Post |date=20 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> he was one of eight candidates for the position. Bambang argued that [[Corruption in Indonesia|corruption in the country]] would most easily be eradicated through preemptive efforts, including not allowing the state or its employees to do cash transactions over [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 10 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2011/10/24/1429367/Ini.Resep.Basmi.Korupsi.Ala.Bambang.Widjojanto |title=Ini Resep Basmi Korupsi Ala Bambang Widjojanto |trans-title=This  is Bambang Widjojanto's Recipe for Eradicating Corruption |last=Liu |first=Hindra |date=24 October 2011 |language=Indonesian |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68yPm8OMq?url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2011/10/24/1429367/Ini.Resep.Basmi.Korupsi.Ala.Bambang.Widjojanto |archivedate=7 July 2012 |work=Kompas |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThough Bambang was considered the favourite, the [[Indonesian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] ultimately selected [[Abraham Samad]] over both Bambang and the incumbent Busyro. Anti-corruption activists expressed disappointment in the decision, stating that Abraham had been selected to please political parties rather than to combat graft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/12/03/house-s-kpk-picks-politically-motivated.html |title=House\u2019s KPK picks 'politically motivated' |date=3 December 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Bambang was still appointed to the Commission, however, and made its Deputy Chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/03/29/kpk-assist-ago-s-investigation-alleged-chevron-graft-case.html |title=KPK to assist AGO\u2019s investigation in alleged Chevron graft case |date=29 March 2012 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n==Controversy==\n===False witnesses===\nHe once presented \"false witnesses\" in the dispute over West Kotawaringin regional election in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tirto.id/yusril-tak-persoalkan-kasus-bw-soal-pernah-hadirkan-saksi-palsu-d6b3. |title=Yusril Tak Persoalkan Kasus BW Soal Pernah Hadirkan Saksi Palsu |date=27 May 2019 |work=tirto.id |access-date=19 June 2019 |language=ID}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award laureates}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widjojanto, Bambang}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Indonesian lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Jakarta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Bambang Widjojanto\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> Bambang Widjojanto.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Portrait as member of KPK\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|08|18}}\n| birth_place = Jakarta\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indonesian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Human rights work\n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Bambang Widjojanto''' (born 18&nbsp;October 1959) is an Indonesian human rights activist. He is the co-founder of the Indonesian Legal Aid Foundation and a \"leading advocate for the rights of the indigenous peoples of West Papua\".<ref name=RFK /> According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', his work for indigenous peoples made him \"the target of repeated threats and detentions by the Indonesian government\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/08/news/08iht-topic_1.html |title=Asian Topics : Around Asia |date=8 October 1993 |author=Arthur Higbee |work=The New York Times |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBambang was born in Jakarta on 18&nbsp;October 1959. He did his undergraduate degree at Jayabaya University, then became a lawyer. By 1986 he was active with legal aid foundations throughout the country. Together with [[Munir Said Thalib]] he helped establish the human rights organisation KontraS; Wijojanto was also involved with the establishment of the Consortium for National Law Reform and the Indonesian Corruption Watch.<ref name=\"KPK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kpk.go.id/modules/commissioners/ |title=Bambang Widjojanto |language=Indonesian |publisher=Corruption Eradication Commission |archivedate=7 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68yOi2mE6?url=http://www.kpk.go.id/modules/commissioners/ |accessdate=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Human rights work ==\nIn 1993, he won the [[Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award]]. Following the award, the [[Robert F. Kennedy Center for Justice and Human Rights]] formed a team of legal experts to assist Bambang in his work.<ref name=RFK>{{cite web |url=http://rfkcenter.org/1993-bambang-widjojanto-indonesia |title=1993: Bambang Widjojanto, Indonesia |publisher=Robert F. Kennedy Center for Justice and Human Rights |accessdate=6 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520232419/http://rfkcenter.org/1993-bambang-widjojanto-indonesia |archive-date=20 May 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he succeeded [[Adnan Buyung Nasution]] as the head of the [[Legal Aid Institute (Jakarta)|Legal Aid Institute]] (LBH, ''Lembaga Bantuan Hukum''), a \"central organisation within the pro-democracy movement\". Bambang's replacement of Nasution caused a schism within the group, and several activists left to form the rival Indonesian Legal Aid and Human Rights Association.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=uV-LLHSQNY0C&pg=PA100&dq=Bambang+Widjojanto#v=onepage&q=Bambang%20Widjojanto&f=false |title=Indonesia and the \"Third Wave of Democratization\": The Indonesian Pro-Democracy Movement in a Changing World |last=Uhlin |first=Anders |year=1997 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0312173838 |page=100 |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The following year, he defended [[Muchtar Pakpahan]], a labour union leader arrested by the government of President [[Suharto]]. The government then attempted to pressure Bambang to testify against his client.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/21/opinion/indonesia-s-cynical-crackdown.html |title=Indonesia's Cynical Crackdown |date=21 January 1997 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nBambang received a master's degree in law from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] in London. In 2005 he graduated from [[Padjadjaran University]] in [[Bandung]] with a master's degree in [[business law]]; this was followed by a doctorate from the same university in 2009. During this period he was on several special commissions, working with the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]] and the prosecutor general's office.<ref name=\"KPK\"/>\n\n== Corruption Eradication Commission candidacies ==\nIn 2010, Bambang was one of two finalists to head Indonesia's [[Corruption Eradication Commission]] (KPK), along with [[Muhammad Busyro Muqoddas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/two-left-in-race-for-anti-graft-job/story-e6frg6so-1225911068199 |title=Two left in race for anti-graft job |author=Peter Alford |date=28 August 2010 |work=The Australian |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Busyro was eventually selected for the position, though President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono offered Bambang a \"consolation post\" heading the Attorney General's Office Commission to reform the [[Indonesian National Police|National Police]] as well as the Attorney General's Office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2010/11/26/sby-offers-consolation-post-bambang-widjojanto.html |title=SBY offers consolation post to Bambang Widjojanto |date=26 November 2010 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Bambang ran again for the office the following year;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/20/noted-activist-gives-kpk-chair-a-second-shot.html |title=Noted activist gives KPK chair a second shot |author=Jakarta Post |date=20 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> he was one of eight candidates for the position. Bambang argued that [[Corruption in Indonesia|corruption in the country]] would most easily be eradicated through preemptive efforts, including not allowing the state or its employees to do cash transactions over [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 10 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2011/10/24/1429367/Ini.Resep.Basmi.Korupsi.Ala.Bambang.Widjojanto |title=Ini Resep Basmi Korupsi Ala Bambang Widjojanto |trans-title=This  is Bambang Widjojanto's Recipe for Eradicating Corruption |last=Liu |first=Hindra |date=24 October 2011 |language=Indonesian |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68yPm8OMq?url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2011/10/24/1429367/Ini.Resep.Basmi.Korupsi.Ala.Bambang.Widjojanto |archivedate=7 July 2012 |work=Kompas |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThough Bambang was considered the favourite, the [[Indonesian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] ultimately selected [[Abraham Samad]] over both Bambang and the incumbent Busyro. Anti-corruption activists expressed disappointment in the decision, stating that Abraham had been selected to please political parties rather than to combat graft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/12/03/house-s-kpk-picks-politically-motivated.html |title=House\u2019s KPK picks 'politically motivated' |date=3 December 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Bambang was still appointed to the Commission, however, and made its Deputy Chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/03/29/kpk-assist-ago-s-investigation-alleged-chevron-graft-case.html |title=KPK to assist AGO\u2019s investigation in alleged Chevron graft case |date=29 March 2012 |work=The Jakarta Post |accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n==Controversy==\n===False witnesses===\nHe once presented \"false witnesses\" in the dispute over West Kotawaringin regional election in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tirto.id/yusril-tak-persoalkan-kasus-bw-soal-pernah-hadirkan-saksi-palsu-d6b3. |title=Yusril Tak Persoalkan Kasus BW Soal Pernah Hadirkan Saksi Palsu |date=27 May 2019 |work=tirto.id |access-date=19 June 2019 |language=ID}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award laureates}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widjojanto, Bambang}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Indonesian lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Jakarta]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bambang_Widjojanto"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands, Finland}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[\u00c5land Islands]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 22 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=22|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 9\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Swedish language|Swedish-speaking]] autonomous region of the [[\u00c5land Islands]] in March 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 22 March, the first case in the \u00c5land Islands was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c5land Islands confirms first coronavirus cases, recommends quarantine for visitors from Finland |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/aland_islands_confirms_first_coronavirus_cases_recommends_quarantine_for_visitors_from_finland/11270010 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Yle |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Aland Islands}}\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Finland|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country subdivision|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the \u00c5land Islands]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{\u00c5land-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands, Finland}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands\n| map1 = \n| places = \n| legend1 =\n| map2 = \n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[\u00c5land Islands]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 22 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=22|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| confirmed_cases = 4\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| total_ili =\n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Swedish language|Swedish-speaking]] autonomous region of the [[\u00c5land Islands]] in March 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 22 March, the first case in the \u00c5land Islands was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c5land Islands confirms first coronavirus cases, recommends quarantine for visitors from Finland |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/aland_islands_confirms_first_coronavirus_cases_recommends_quarantine_for_visitors_from_finland/11270010 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Yle |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Aland Islands}}\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Finland|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country subdivision|\u00c5land Islands]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the \u00c5land Islands]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{\u00c5land-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Miglix519", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fresh info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_%C3%85land_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Guardbridge railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name = Guardbridge\n| locale = [[Guardbridge]]\n| borough = [[Fife]]\n| coordinates =\n{{coord|56.3596|-2.8906|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:2000_source:Google| display=inline, title}}\n| gridref  = NO450189\n| original = [[The St. Andrews Railway|St Andrews Railway]]\n| pregroup = [[North British Railway]]\n| postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]]\n| platforms = 1\n| years = {{Start date|1862|07|01|df=yes}}\n| events = Station opened\n| years1 = {{End date|1965|09|06|df=y}}\n| events1 = Station closed to passengers and goods traffic\n}}\n'''Guardbridge railway station''' served the village of [[Guardbridge]], [[Fife]], Scotland from 1862 to 1965 on [[The St. Andrews Railway]].\n\n== History ==\nThe station opened on 1 July 1862 by [[The St. Andrews Railway]]. The station closed to both passengers and goods traffic on 6 September 1965.<ref name=GuardbridgeStationInfo>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/32887/guardbridge-station|title=Guardbridge Station|work=Canmore|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{rail line |next={{rws|Leuchars}}<br><small>Line and station open</small>|previous={{rws|St Andrews (New)}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[The St. Andrews Railway]]|col={{NBR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Fife]]\n[[Category:Former North British Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1862]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1965]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1965 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in Scotland]]\n{{Scotland-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name = Guardbridge\n| locale = [[Guardbridge]]\n| borough = [[Fife]]\n| coordinates =\n{{coord|56.3596|-2.8906|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:2000_source:Google| display=inline, title}}\n| gridref  = NO450189\n| original = [[The St. Andrews Railway|St Andrews Railway]]\n| pregroup = [[North British Railway]]\n| postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]]\n| platforms = 1\n| years = {{Start date|1862|07|01|df=yes}}\n| events = Station opened\n| years1 = {{End date|1965|09|06|df=y}}\n| events1 = Station closed to passengers and goods traffic\n}}\n'''Guardbridge railway station''' served the village of [[Guardbridge]], [[Fife]], Scotland from 1862 to 1965 on [[The St. Andrews Railway]].\n\n== History ==\nThe station opened on 1 July 1862 by [[The St. Andrews Railway]]. The station closed to both passengers and goods traffic on 6 September 1965.<ref name=GuardbridgeStationInfo>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/32887/guardbridge-station|title=Guardbridge Station|work=Canmore|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{rail line |next={{rws|Leuchars}}<br><small>Line and station open</small>|previous={{rws|St Andrews(New)}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[The St. Andrews Railway]]|col={{NBR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Fife]]\n[[Category:Former North British Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1862]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1965]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1965 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in Scotland]]\n{{Scotland-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Steamybrian2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guardbridge_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Club Nation", "text_new": "{{for|the album by Richard Evans|Club Nation (album)}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name          = Club Nation R\u00e1dio\n| format             = [[Trance music|Trance]], [[Progressive music#Electronic|Progressive]]\n| runtime            = 2 Hours\n| creator            = Tezija & Keyra\n| starring           = Tezija & Keyra and Various Guests\n| country            = {{Flag icon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]]\n                       {{Flag icon|Croatia}} [[Croatia]]\n| home_station       = Transam\u00e9rica Internacional | first_aired        = February 13, 2009\n| last_aired         = Present\n| num_episodes       = <!-- Do not edit number of episodes as it will update itself, unless the show stops airing-->{{Age in weeks|month1=02|day1=10|year1=2009|month2={{CURRENTMONTH}}|day2={{CURRENTDAY}}|year2={{CURRENTYEAR}}}}\n| website            = [http://www.clubnation.nl/ Club Nation]\n}}\n\n'''Club Nation''' is a weekly [[radio show]] hosted by the [[Croatia]]n/[[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[discjockey|dj]] duo Tezija & Keyra, that is broadcast worldwide by over 30 [[radio station]]s.\nThe show takes the format of a two-hour mix in which they play new [[trance music]], both [[Promotional recording|promotional]] and commercially released.\n\nClub Nation was first broadcast on 13 February 2009 on the commercial Dutch station Splash FM. The station lost its FM frequency and the [[Japan]]ese FM station ''Rede Transam\u00e9rica Internacional'' decided to continue broadcasting Club Nation. After this more FM and web stations around the world followed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubnationradio.com/about/#.Xi5W83VKjeQ|title=About|last=Boaventura|first=Paulo|date=January 27, 2020|website=Club Nation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=https://www.clubnationradio.com/about/#.Xi5W83VKjeQ}}</ref>\n\nThe show is supported by worldwide known DJs with a guest mix, DJs like [[Gareth Emery]], [[Cosmic Gate]], [[TyDi]], [[Ferry Corsten]] and [[Judge Jules]] have already been in the show.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Broadcasts==\n===Netherlands===\n\nAB-Radio 105.8<br>\nRadio 350 92.3<br>\nAtos RTV 106.1<br>\nTynaarlo Lokaal 105.9<br>\nRadio Hengelo 105.8<br>\nExcellentFM 104.9<br>\nBoschtion FM 95.2<br>\nRadio Polderland 106.0<br>\nZap! FM 107.9<br>\nRTW FM 105.8<br>\nRadio President 107.9<br>\nSluttieFM<br>\nNew Dance Radio<br>\nAktief FM<br>\nCentrumRadio Rotterdam<br>\nNetwork Radio 1 <br>\nRadio 105<br>\nNow! FM\n\n===Belgium===\nRadio M FM 107.5 / 107.6 / 107.2<br>\nThals FM 105.7<br>\nRadio Brouwer FM 106.3<br>\nAccent FM<br>\nText Radio<br>\n\n===Other countries===\nClub Lounge Radio (Trance Channel) [[Germany]]<br>\nTrance Clubber Radio [[England]]<br>\nRede Transam\u00e9rica International 76.5 [[Japan]]<br>\nSafari Radio 104.7 FM [[Greece]]<br>\nTurnON Radio International [[United States]]<br>\nRadio Napa 106.3 FM [[Cyprus]]<br>\nTrancefan [[Germany]]<br>\nEmsradio [[Poland]]<br>\nTrance Radio CH [[Switzerland]]<br>\nRapture Radio [[England]]<br>\nHALOradio<br>\nRadio Dj-Fm [[Albania]]<br>\nSSRadio Hard and Fast [[England]]<br>\nKiss FM [[Ireland]]<br>\nTune FM [[United States]]<br>\nMegaBPM [[Germany]]<br>\nHKGFM [[Hongkong]]<br>\nElectronic Clubsounds [[Germany]]<br>\nTrance Vibrations [[Romania]]<br>\nRadio Net [[Colombia]]<br>\nLive Mix [[Brazil]]\n\n==Playlists==\n[[Playlist]]s for every episode can be found at the official [http://www.clubnation.nl/ Club Nation] website.\n\n==Regular features==\nEach broadcast features the ''Tune of the Week'', ''Classic of the week'' and the ''Club Nation guest mix''.\n\n===Tune of the Week===\nThe '''Tune of the Week''' is selected by Tezija & Keyra and most of the time a not yet released track.\n\n===Classic of the week===\nThe '''Classic of the week''' is a track from the past years.\n\n===Club Nation guest mix===\nThe '''Club Nation guest mix''' is a 30 minutes guest mix by a known dj from around the world. In some special episodes the guest mix is 1 hour.\n\n===Club Nation Records===\nIn 2010 Tezija & Keyra started their record label Club Nation Records, the artists on this label are worldwide promoted in the radio show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubnationradio.com/|title=Nation Radio Club|last=Boaventura|first=Paulo|date=January 27, 2020|website=Nation Radio Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=https://www.clubnationradio.com/}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.clubnation.nl/ Official Club Nation website]\n*[http://www.clubnationrecords.com/ Club Nation Records website]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dutch music radio programs]]\n[[Category:Electronic music radio shows]]\n[[Category:Trance music]]\n[[Category:2009 radio programme debuts]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the album by Richard Evans|Club Nation (album)}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name          = Club Nation R\u00e1dio\n| format             = [[Trance music|Trance]], [[Progressive music#Electronic|Progressive]]\n| runtime            = 2 Hours\n| creator            = Tezija & Keyra\n| starring           = Tezija & Keyra and Various Guests\n| country            = {{Flag icon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]]\n                       {{Flag icon|Croatia}} [[Croatia]]\n| home_station       = Transam\u00e9rica Internacional | first_aired        = February 13, 2009\n| last_aired         = Present\n| num_episodes       = <!-- Do not edit number of episodes as it will update itself, unless the show stops airing-->{{Age in weeks|month1=02|day1=10|year1=2009|month2={{CURRENTMONTH}}|day2={{CURRENTDAY}}|year2={{CURRENTYEAR}}}}\n| website            = [http://www.clubnation.nl/ Club Nation]\n}}\n\n'''Club Nation''' is a weekly [[radio show]] hosted by the [[Croatia]]n/[[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[discjockey|dj]] duo Tezija & Keyra, that is broadcast worldwide by over 30 [[radio station]]s.\nThe show takes the format of a two-hour mix in which they play new [[trance music]], both [[Promotional recording|promotional]] and commercially released.\n\nClub Nation was first broadcast on 13 February 2009 on the commercial Dutch station Splash FM. The station lost its FM frequency and the [[Japan]]ese FM station ''Rede Transam\u00e9rica Internacional'' decided to continue broadcasting Club Nation. After this more FM and web stations around the world followed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubnationradio.com/about/#.Xi5W83VKjeQ|title=About|last=Boaventura|first=Paulo|date=January 27, 2020|website=Club Nation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=https://www.clubnationradio.com/about/#.Xi5W83VKjeQ}}</ref>\n\nThe show is supported by worldwide known dj's with a guest mix, dj's like [[Gareth Emery]], [[Cosmic Gate]], [[TyDi]], [[Ferry Corsten]] and [[Judge Jules]] have already been in the show.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Broadcasts==\n===Netherlands===\n\nAB-Radio 105.8<br>\nRadio 350 92.3<br>\nAtos RTV 106.1<br>\nTynaarlo Lokaal 105.9<br>\nRadio Hengelo 105.8<br>\nExcellentFM 104.9<br>\nBoschtion FM 95.2<br>\nRadio Polderland 106.0<br>\nZap! FM 107.9<br>\nRTW FM 105.8<br>\nRadio President 107.9<br>\nSluttieFM<br>\nNew Dance Radio<br>\nAktief FM<br>\nCentrumRadio Rotterdam<br>\nNetwork Radio 1 <br>\nRadio 105<br>\nNow! FM\n\n===Belgium===\nRadio M FM 107.5 / 107.6 / 107.2<br>\nThals FM 105.7<br>\nRadio Brouwer FM 106.3<br>\nAccent FM<br>\nText Radio<br>\n\n===Other countries===\nClub Lounge Radio (Trance Channel) [[Germany]]<br>\nTrance Clubber Radio [[England]]<br>\nRede Transam\u00e9rica International 76.5 [[Japan]]<br>\nSafari Radio 104.7 FM [[Greece]]<br>\nTurnON Radio International [[United States]]<br>\nRadio Napa 106.3 FM [[Cyprus]]<br>\nTrancefan [[Germany]]<br>\nEmsradio [[Poland]]<br>\nTrance Radio CH [[Switzerland]]<br>\nRapture Radio [[England]]<br>\nHALOradio<br>\nRadio Dj-Fm [[Albania]]<br>\nSSRadio Hard and Fast [[England]]<br>\nKiss FM [[Ireland]]<br>\nTune FM [[United States]]<br>\nMegaBPM [[Germany]]<br>\nHKGFM [[Hongkong]]<